<br>
Let's imagine that the coding takes the total number of people who were hit by the spell, and then calculates the percentage of them who returned a &quot;did not take hold&quot; result.  It returns that percentage of the mana and reagents used.<br>
<br>
For example:  I cast Hand of Virtue on a group of six people, but three of them have Blessing of the Nine already.  That means that the spell costs me half the mana and half the number of peridots that it ought to, or 1250 mana and 1 peridot.<br>
<br>
At least, I think that's what you were suggesting.<br>
<br>
Well, now let's imagine that I kick two people from that group and cast HoV so that it only affects one person.  Hey presto!  I just cast V for less than 500 mana with no peridot cost at all!  Let's all rotate in and out of that exp group, people.<br>
<br>
Honestly, if they're going to allow that, what they ought to do is to take the peridot cost off Virtue completely.<br>
<br>
Incidentally, there's a serious case for doing that.  After all, enchanters don't use peridots for their runes any more, and shamans don't use emeralds for avatar... <p><!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>too fuckin bad man, youre out of luck. im not wasting more mana for your stupidty.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
